ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical composition of the TiO2-, ZnO- and SnO2- catalysts supported on SBA-15 was analyzed by SEM-EDX (Table 1
                        ). In all cases, the results showed values close to the expected nominal charge of the deposited metal oxide (30 wt %). The element mapping results for the catalysts are shown in Fig. 1
                        . It was observed that the supported metal oxides were distributed evenly on the SBA-15 surface.

The powder XRD patterns of all samples (support and catalysts) showed a broad peak between 15 and 35° (2θ) due to the amorphous silica of the SBA-15 support (Fig. 4
                        A). Additionally, TiO2/SBA-15 and SnO2/SBA-15 catalysts exhibited diffraction peaks of TiO2 and SnO2 crystalline phases. Thus, reflections at 25.4, 38.0, 48.0, 54.1, 55.0 and 62.9° (2θ) were observed in the diffractogram of the TiO2/SBA-15 sample, which match well with the (101), (004), (200), (105), (211) and (204) diffraction planes, respectively, of the TiO2 anatase crystalline structure (JCPDS 21–1272). The SnO2/SBA-15 sample revealed a larger number of diffraction peaks at 26.5, 33.8, 37.9, 39.0, 51.8, 54.7, 57.8, 61.8, 64.7, 66.0, 71.2 and 78.7° (2θ) that correspond to the (110), (101), (200), (111), (211), (220), (002), (310), (112), (301), (202) and (321) crystallographic planes of the tetragonal structure of the SnO2 cassiterite (JCPDS 41–1445). The mean crystallite sizes determined by the Scherrer equation for the TiO2/SBA-15 and SnO2/SBA-15 catalysts were 8.8 and 10.5 nm for TiO2 and SnO2, respectively (Table 2
                        ). It is worth to mention that these values are larger than the mesopore diameters of the catalysts (Table 1), suggesting that these crystals are located on the external surface of the SBA-15 support. In contrast, no diffraction peaks of a ZnO crystalline phase were observed for the ZnO/SBA-15 sample. Only a broad low-intensity shoulder located in a 30–40°(2θ) range was noticed in addition to a wide signal of the amorphous silica of the SBA-15 support. This suggests a better dispersion of the deposited ZnO species than that of the TiO2 and SnO2 ones in the corresponding SBA-15-supported catalysts. Fig. 4B shows for comparison the crystalline phases present on the unsupported commercial TiO2, ZnO and SnO2 nanopowders and titania Degussa P25, while the corresponding crystallite sizes are presented in Table 2. It can be noted that all unsupported nanopowders had larger crystallite size than metal oxides supported on SBA-15.

The prepared TiO2/SBA-15, ZnO/SBA-15 and SnO2/SBA-15 catalysts and the commercial TiO2, ZnO and SnO2 nanopowders were evaluated in the photocatalytic degradation of methylene blue (MB) dye upon UV irradiation. Titania Degussa P25 was also tested as a reference catalyst. All photocatalytic experiments were performed maintaining constant the amount of the active phase (6 mg of the semiconductor metal oxide) in order to obtain activity results that can be compared (Table 3
                        ). In the first set of experiments, the adsorption-desorption equilibrium of MB on the catalysts' surface was evaluated previous to the photocatalytic measurements, as mentioned in the experimental section. Fig. 8
                        A shows the change in the concentration of MB for 120 min in the dark to reach the adsorption-desorption equilibrium followed by UV irradiation for another 120 min. It was observed that the MB adsorption on the TiO2 P25 surface, as well as on unsupported commercial nanopowders, was almost negligible in the dark period (Table 3). In contrast, all the SBA-15-supported catalysts exhibited significant adsorption capacity of MB in the dark achieving the adsorption-desorption equilibrium at about 60 min (Fig. 8A). At the end of the adsorption stage, the TiO2/SBA-15 and SnO2/SBA-15 catalysts showed a ∼30% decolorization of the MB solution, while the ZnO/SBA-15 catalyst showed the highest MB adsorption capacity with ∼50% decolorization. These results do not seem to be surprising, since all SBA-15-supported catalysts possess high surface area and relatively large pores (Table 1) facilitating MB adsorption. In addition, the surface charges of the used materials at neutral pH (7) of MB solution should be considered, because the adsorption of cationic or anionic organic dyes is due mainly to their electrostatic interaction with the catalyst's surface [25,37–39]. Thus, at a neutral pH, the MB dye is present in solution in cationic form (MB+) and it can be expected that it would have a strong electrostatic attraction to the negatively charged surfaces and repulsion from the positively charged ones. The IEP values (Table 2) show that the synthesized SBA-15-supported catalysts and pristine SBA-15 silica (IE points between 2.3 and 5.8) have the appropriate negative surface charge at neutral pH, facilitating the adsorption of MB+ species, which explains their high adsorption capacity. In the case of the titania P25 catalyst, its isoelectric point (IEP 6.9) was very close to the solution's pH, leading to almost neutral surface charge and, consequently, low adsorption capacity for the MB dye. On the other hand, the adsorption behavior of the ZnO nanopowder and the ZnO/SBA-15 catalyst was different from all other materials. Thus, the unsupported ZnO nanopowder showed the highest MB adsorption (1.4%, Table 3) among other commercial metal oxides, which cannot be attributed to the electrostatic attraction, since both MB+ and the ZnO surface (IEP 9.4) are charged positively. Similarly, the ZnO/SBA-15 catalyst had almost twice higher MB adsorption capacity than the TiO2/SBA-15 one, in spite of the fact that both of them had similar IEP values (5.8 and 5.6, respectively, Table 2). These results point out that for the ZnO-containing materials, not only the electrostatic interactions are responsible for the MB adsorption. In this line, a recent study on the removal of both cationic and anionic dyes by ZnO nanoparticles [40] evidenced that ZnO was able to adsorb cationic dye (malachite green, MG) by the chemical precipitation mechanism. Thus, the zeta potential of ZnO nanoparticles at an almost neutral pH (6.3) of the purified water was positive (13.1 mV), which was attributed to the presence of Zn(OH)+ surface species. The chemical interaction between basic OH− groups of the above-mentioned species and the malachite green cation (MG+) was responsible for the precipitation of MG dye on the ZnO surface. It seems that the above precipitation mechanism is also applicable for the adsorption of cationic methylene blue dye on ZnO nanopowder and ZnO/SBA-15 materials used in the present work.

Finally, the deposition of the photocatalytically active metal oxides on the mesoporous SBA-15 support had another advantage compared with the titania P25 reference, which consists in the easy and quick separation of the catalysts after the photocatalytic tests (Fig. 10
                        ). This is an important issue for the possible reuse of the prepared photocatalysts. Fig. 11
                         shows results obtained with the TiO2/SBA-15 catalyst, which was separated from the reaction mixture at the end of the reaction and reused two times without any additional treatment. It can be noted that the adsorption capacity of this catalyst was maintained almost unchanged in the three cycles of the usage. However, the decolorization and mineralization of MB decreased, that can be ascribed to the accumulation of the adsorbed MB molecules on the catalyst surface. Possibly, the calcination of the catalyst in air after several cycles of usage for the elimination of the adsorbed MB dye could regenerate the catalyst and improve its photocatalytic performance. However, this point needs further experimental study.
